Notes: negative water table depths denote surface water, depth to peat. No 3 cm temperatures- soil temps denote water temperature.  | Notes_additional: Forgot one set of 47 mm filter papers, so DOC samples were filtered at lab on July 12, ~16:00 from collected whole water samples. Eriophorum and sphagnum cores suffered a fair deal of compression, though difficult to quantify. Will likely need to use Wardenaar next time- will cause time constraint. Pore water sampling is quite time consumptive. Will not be able to 'suck' and core in the same day with only 2 ppl. If using Waardenaar. When collecting extra 1 cm section for bulk isotope/biogeochem samples, S and D was always 1 cm below microbial interval, M was always 1 cm above microbial interval. Bulk samples were refrigerated over night and split on the morning of the 13th. One should not use field styrofoam vial rack in -80 freezer if it has been a wet day. Instead one should dry the vials and transfer to new, dry cylinder rack. They freeze very tightly in place and make a mess of the foam when removing to tranfer into cryo-box.

Eriophorum and sphagnum cores suffered a fair deal of compression, though difficult to quantify. Will likely need to use Wardenaar next time- will cause time constraint. Pore water sampling is quite time consumptive. Will not be able to 'suck' and core in the same day with only 2 ppl. If using Waardenaar. When collecting extra 1 cm section for bulk isotope/biogeochem samples, S and D was always 1 cm below microbial interval, M was always 1 cm above microbial interval. Bulk samples were refrigerated over night and split on the morning of the 13th. One should not use field styrofoam vial rack in -80 freezer if it has been a wet day. Instead one should dry the vials and transfer to new, dry cylinder rack. They freeze very tightly in place and make a mess of the foam when removing to tranfer into cryo-box.

Notes__.DepthInfo: Notes: Core 2, Sky cored. | QualityFlag__.DepthInfo: Water table depth (WTD) note: The WTD sign convention for this field campaign was ambiguous, and/or the WTD signs for some of the sites were questionable. The originally-recorded WTDs are in the column "Water_Table_Depth_WTD.cm", and the sign-resolved WTDs (based on emails between Virginia Rich and Suzanne Hodgkins) are in the column "WTD.cm_neg_is_below_sfc__". For this core, the WTD was assumed to be below the surface because the site is a bog. In addition, there was no porewater pH recorded for the surface samples. However, the WTD being below isn’t 100% certain, as Nicole’s note says "positive=above surface," and also the site in general was unusually wet this year. Note from Virginia Rich: "I think that is above; Nicole was attentive to detail and her note is unambiguous, and it was reported as a wet time. I would feel very certain of this but 11cm over the surface seems like a lot. It’s worth looking at the site photo of that time. Nicole loves photography so I’d think there’s good pics for that year." In response, Suzanne looked in the Google Drive folder for 2017 and didn’t find any photos; however, Patrick Crill’s sensor data says the WTD was 9cm below the surface on that same date. This, combined with the lack of porewater measurements at the surface, led to the consensus that the WTD for these cores was below the surface.
